 A longer version moving on the sports wire.</NOTE> <HEAD>LaserPhotos OLY1,3,6,35</HEAD> <BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE> <BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE> <DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE> <TEXT> Canadian Ben Johnson left the Olympics today ``in a complete state of shock,'' accused of cheating with drugs in the world's fastest 100-meter dash and stripped of his gold medal.
 Many athletes accepted the accusation that Johnson used a muscle-building but dangerous and illegal anabolic steroid called stanozolol as confirmation of what they said they know has been going on in track and field. ``Everybody uses drugs,'' said sprinter Horace Dove-Edwin of Sierra Leone. ``Give me a break ... they have everything.
 You can get it anywhere.'' Red-eyed and visibly distraught, Johnson's sister, Clare Rodney in suburban Toronto, refused to believe the accusation. ``If you could cut him into a million pieces and test him over again, my brother is not on drugs,'' she said.
 The world's fastest human also was automatically suspended from international competition for two years and banned from Canada's national team for life. ``He appeared to be in a complete state of shock and not comprehending the situation,'' said Canada's chief of mission, Carol Anne Letheren. ``Ben was not able to discuss or articulate anything at that moment ...
